content: Hello all, we will now start renju lesson.
我有个朋友一直在的，刚才掉了，能让他进来吗？他没有学生ID：（不会英语，请原谅
First of all, I am sorry for the delays of website and class.
for some reasons, I cannot be very fast.
Today, we will look at the game from 1985,
played by two great Japanese masters,
do you know the famous names
Nara Hideki is so famous for us because he participated most times in WC.
Tomimori Shigeru is famous too, but maybe nowadays people know him by another name.
At some point of his life, Tomimori stopped using his real name for renju,
and made a new identity as a renju artist.
Today he uses name Makoto Yamaguchi for renju.
His face very attractive, i saw his photo
and those who still dont know, he is the current Japanese champion.
and today, he came to ORC game server for the first time
Many people like his rule,and me:)
since yama+guchi means mountain door... so the written characters LLI (shan) and O (kou) represent his id
as you know, Nara likes white color a lot.
he is a good defence player.
At that time, the classic 7th moves, such as 7-i8 and 7-g10 were popular
These 11 moves were quite common moves.

wolfzhou, luwenzhe, span, slamduk, Padovan, iris, dhalsim, LiuJianping, shaoping, bawangwan, coco_yuang, callings, fallnavy, yyfcsd, killer21st, Aurora, Intotherenju, mcmanus, endlessroad, liuwenming, shuwang, virag, mikn1, sosei, moocheng, Xespok, Silver, zhp3410, QBEN, casar, sunrain, mayhem, H8, concord2497.
here white can have 3 different tactics,
currently, I still dont know for sure,
which of them is most profitable for white
not easy to know, seldom played
if I remember correct, the 12th move was invented by a Japanese named Matsuura
but maybe the outcome is not so good, if black defends properly, i forgot.
which reminds me a quick win I got in my first big tournament in 1989 in Russia.
so I thought the move 12 is good enough.
yes calm, and block everything upper side
Nara is known for his defenseive planning,
he like to play 100 move games :)
his average games are longer than most other masters.
which is nice - he can enjoy longer renju
How should white respond to this 13th move?
I think, this choice depends from players personality and tactics.
aggressive players might try some attacking here
white peaceful players try to balance first,
this is exactly where he played
how should black deal with it?
you can go back and try other
anyway, white is not bad here
ok maybe not so important here
thanks for helping to test the variant
we did not make conclusions about the active style,
but at least it seems its possible for white.
as yy predicted, Nara chose passive 14th move.
Young and brave Tomimori launced and immediate attack.

Padovan, wolfzhou, slamduk, tunnet99, span, endlessroad, mayhem, moocheng, Aurora, Silver, concord2497, shaoping, dhalsim, bawangwan, liuwenming, mcmanus, shuwang, swordblue, LiuJianping, fallnavy, luwenzhe, Intotherenju, Xespok, sosei, virag, callings, sunrain, H8, mikn1, bm, zhp3410, casar.
why would black need g11 point?
is white planning to play to that point?
to prevent white play e9 perhaps:)
it looks to me that black is slowly increasing the power
but its just in first look.
maybe in deeper look we find out,
that Nara had no choice already.
you will give up here or continue?
we dont look for shortest, or most beautiful, or hardest
usually, we just place any win,
to save the time of lesson
maybe can be better, this way easy for calculating
maybe Nara's passive 24 is giving white some chance.
It is so much inside stone,
black will now even have e8 support.
maybe this is better indeed, thanks tunnet
black is now finally attacking straight
He cannot defend both left and right sides at the same time.
Tomimori has winning power in both areas.
why did black attack on the left side anyway,
if he later continued on right side like this.
You will see the answer now.
The purpose of left side development was to create one additional connection,
that black will need in the final of attack.
because of f8 and i5 connection,
white cannot afford to let black take the k7 point.
so Nara was forced to use white fours
while white has to defend against both vcfs,
so there are just i12 and k9 moves possible
k9 makes cut for g11, j11 vcf
but the ending was still fast
Shigeru Tomimori had got a brilliant victory,
in such early times of renju theory,
I am glad we had a chance to study this variant and I hope you all found something useful to think about from this.
The lesson is over now, see you all next week. Thank you!
